SUMMARIZER="F">

Ronald Spiers, a veteran US diplomat will be the new undersecretary-general
for General Assembly affairs at the UN. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar announced the appointment. This is the top ranking American post at
the world body and Spiers will replace Joseph Reed, a banker who served in
that post until since 1983.  Reed will become chief of protocol for the
United States.  Spiers is a career foreign service officer and has been
ambassador to the Bahamas and Turkey and, from 1981 until 1983 was
ambassador to Pakistan.  Spiers most recent job was undersecretary of state
for management affairs.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890715-0076"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="F">

Joseph Gildenhorn, named by President Bush to be ambassador to Switzerland
has been rated "unqualified" by the American Academy of Diplomacy, an
organization composed of former high ranking diplomats including all living
former secretaries of state.  Gildenhorn, a lawyer and real estate
developer, and his family have given nearly $230,000 to Republican campaigns
since 1984.  A State Department report said that Gildenhorn would make an
excellent candidate for ambassadorship and also noted that he has been a
strong Republican supporter, citing his money contributions.  Three other
candidates for ambassadorships have also been rated unqualified by the
Academy of Diplomacy.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA072689-0050"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="F">

Three of President Bush's ambassadorial nominees won narrow approval from
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.  Democrats said the only
qualifications of the three were political connections.  Those nominees were
Joseph Zappala for Spain, Marvin Sembler for Australia, and Della Newman for
New Zealand.  Senator Paul Sarbanes led the opposition in committee and
vowed to carry the fight to the Senate floor.  The committee routinely
approved Shirley Temple Black for Czechoslovakia. Other ambassadorial
approvals were Thomas Melady to the Vatican, Keith Brown to Denmark and
Joseph Gildenhorn to Switzerland. William Howard Taft IV was approved to be
US representative on the council of NATO.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900102-0114"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="F">

President Bush named career diplomat Deane Hinton as ambassador to Panama as
a recess appointment since Congress is not in session.  Hinton, currently
ambassador to Costa Rica, replaces Arthur Davis who had been recalled in
protest of what the administration considered the stealing of the Panamanian
elections by General Manuel Noriega.  Davis was later returned to Panama
after US forces invaded Panama and Guillermo Endara was installed as
president.  Hinton has also been ambassador to El Salvador and Pakistan.
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell called Hinton highly qualified
because of his "wide-ranging experience and expertise in Central America".</SUM>

<SUM
